        <div>
            <pb facs="#TL-0569.jpg" n="part4_p095.jpg" xml:id="img_0095" corresp="https://id.acdh.oeaw.ac.at/tillich-lectures/part4_p095.jpg"/>
            
            <p facs="#facs_95_tr_2">
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_2_tl_1" n="N001"/>des
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_2_tl_2" n="N002"/>-564
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_2_tl_3" n="N003"/>infinity, is unsolvable for him, and he trees to get rid of it by returning to something which is less
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_2_tl_4" n="N004"/>than human.
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_2_tl_5" n="N005"/>In the same way, all highly individualized leslures have a tendency to return to primitive
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_2_tl_6" n="N006"/>collecticism. And this is so important because it was a characteristic of ourbringing, where
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_2_tl_7" n="N007"/>at the end of the 19th century, individualism (in the one sense which I gave you) was developed to
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_2_tl_8" n="N008"/>individual
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_2_tl_9" n="N009"/>subject, the completelyauseparated personality, was unable to exist
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_2_tl_10" n="N010"/>such a degree that the
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_2_tl_11" n="N011"/>any longer; and especially in the younger generation of the early 20th century, in the different
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_2_tl_12" n="N012"/>youth Eovements, the tendency to return to the group prevailed. This was theuslle soil
            </p>
            <p facs="#facs_95_tr_3">
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_3_tl_1" n="N001"/>for the other neo-collectivistic movements which appeared both as Communism and as Fascism
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_3_tl_2" n="N002"/>and Nazism.
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_3_tl_3" n="N003"/>Now in order to discuss this situation, I suggest some distinctions. All this has not
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_3_tl_4" n="N004"/>happened in England, while it happened in Continental Europe. It has not happened in this
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_3_tl_5" n="N005"/>country either. Why not? Because in England we have another form of existence over against
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_3_tl_6" n="N006"/>Continental individualism, namely conformism. Let's look at this word for a moment. Conformism
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_3_tl_7" n="N007"/>can be understood in a merely negative sense, namely as subjecting oneself to the laws of convention,
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_3_tl_8" n="N008"/>toferoid being outstanding, standing on oneself, or as Ike formulated it in the courage to Be, the
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_3_tl_9" n="N009"/>courage to be oneself. Where this is lacking, there, conformism can develop. But conformism is,
            </p>
            <p facs="#facs_95_tr_1">
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_1_tl_1" n="N001"/>like all "isms", something which is verballyontical, is negative. Whenever we look at British
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_1_tl_2" n="N002"/>life, we wouldn’t call it conformism in this negative sense, although it has conformistic elements
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_1_tl_3" n="N003"/>in it; but we would call it a system of conformity. And perhaps it is wise to distinguish these
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_1_tl_4" n="N004"/>Mais elle est vrai en lʼannée est
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_1_tl_5" n="N005"/>Gouillez lʼhonneur et très obéissantur, et le dernier étrangères
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_1_tl_6" n="N006"/>dʼauteur ses
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_1_tl_7" n="N007"/>Monsieur,
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_1_tl_8" n="N008"/>dʼavoir lʼautre beaucoup
               <lb facs="#facs_95_tr_1_tl_9" n="N009"/>dʼune manière beaucoup dʼaprès de lʼaresse
            </p>
            
